vectorData.altText: That's right!  The posterior cerebral arteries (PCA) arise from the bifurcation of basilar artery (BA). The bilateral PCAs wrap around the midbrain.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Each ICA gives off a branch, the anterior cerebral artery (ACA) which turns medially to enter the median longitudinal fissure, and continues on the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere. The two ACAs are joined across the midline by the anterior communicating artery (ACom).
Each ICA continues in the lateral fissure as the middle cerebral artery (MCA).
Meanwhile, back at the foramen magnum..

The VAs enter alongside the medulla. At the pontomedullary junction, they unite, forming the basilar arteries (BA). The BA ascends over the belly of the pons, and at the junction of the pons and midbrain, it bifurcates, forming the two posterior cerebral arteries (PCA). The PCAs wrap around the mibrain.
The PCAs and ICAs are joined by the posterior communicating arteries (PCom).
